### How this would be used

```ts
const map = new SignalMap<string, number>();

const selectedId = signal('a');

const doubled = computed(() => {
  const id = selectedId();
  const value = map.get(id) ?? 0;
  return value * 2;
});

effect(() => {
  console.log('Doubled:', doubled());
});

// Elsewhere:
map.set('a', 1);  // only consumers that read key 'a' are invalidated
map.set('b', 10); // does NOT affect the above computed, since it never read 'b'
```

### Alternatives considered

- Single `signal<Map<K, V> | T[] | Set<T>>`
   Simple but coarse: any change invalidates all consumers, even if they only care about one key/index/element.
- A `signal()` per key / index / element
   Works, but boilerplate-heavy and error-prone:
   - need to manage lifecycle of each per-key/element signal (creation, deletion),
   - need separate structures for structure vs. values,
   - cannot easily express collections-of-signals in a reusable, composable way.
- Hand-rolled abstractions on top of @angular/core/primitives/signals
   Possible (and the example above shows how), but:
  - everyone has to reinvent essentially the same patterns,
  - there’s no shared, documented set of best practices for reactive collections,
  - many teams would prefer a higher-level API similar in ergonomics to signal().

